## 8. Rule Priority and Evaluation Order

| Priority (number) | Evaluated | Notes |
|-------------------|-----------|-------|
| **1** | First | Lowest number = highest priority = checked first |
| **2** | Second | |
| **5** | Fifth | |
| **10** | Tenth | |

**First match wins.** If Priority 1 is an Allow rule that matches the request, Priority 5 Block rule never runs.

**Common mistake:** An Allow rule at Priority 2 allows all traffic to `example.com`. Your Block rule at Priority 5 for `app.example.com` never triggers because the Allow already matched.

**Fix:** Either move the Block rule to a lower priority number (e.g. 1) so it runs first, or add an exclusion to the Allow rule so it doesn't match `app.example.com`.

