## 10. DNS (Route 53) + ALB + WAF — How They Fit Together

```
Browser → DNS lookup → Route 53 → returns ALB IP/CNAME
                                          │
Browser → HTTPS request → ALB ← WAF (Web ACL attached here)
                            │
                            ▼
                        Target Group → App (EC2, ECS, EKS, Lambda)
```

### Setting up a new domain with WAF restriction

| Step | What | Where |
|------|------|-------|
| 1 | Create DNS record | Route 53: A record (alias) or CNAME → ALB |
| 2 | Attach certificate | ACM: request cert for `app.example.com`; attach to ALB HTTPS listener |
| 3 | Create IP set | WAF: create `my-internal-ip-set` with allowed CIDRs |
| 4 | Create/update WAF rule | WAF: add rule to Web ACL (Host + NOT IP → Block) |
| 5 | Attach Web ACL to ALB | WAF: associate Web ACL with the ALB |
| 6 | Test | curl from allowed IP → 200; curl from other IP → 403 |

### Route 53 record types

| Type | Use case |
|------|----------|
| **A (Alias)** | Point to an AWS resource (ALB, CloudFront) by alias — no extra DNS hop |
| **CNAME** | Point to any hostname (e.g. ALB DNS name) — adds a DNS hop |

**Alias is preferred** for AWS resources (no charge for alias queries, works at zone apex).

### Verification

```bash
# Check DNS resolves
dig app.example.com
# or
host app.example.com

# Should return the ALB IP or ALB DNS name
```

