## 12. Testing and Verification

### Quick test from terminal

```bash
# 1. Check your current public IP
curl -s ifconfig.me

# 2. Set your target URL
TARGET="https://app.example.com"

# 3. Request the protected resource — check HTTP status code
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" "$TARGET/api/v1/protected/"
# Expected: 403 (if your IP is NOT in the allowed set)
# Expected: 200 (if your IP IS in the allowed set)

# 4. Sanity check — request a different path (not protected by this rule)
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" "$TARGET/api/v1/other/"
# Expected: 200 or 404 (not blocked by WAF)
```

### Test matrix

| Your IP | Path | Expected |
|---------|------|----------|
| In allowed set | Protected path | 200 (or app response) |
| NOT in allowed set | Protected path | **403** (blocked by WAF) |
| NOT in allowed set | Other path | Not blocked (200/404/etc.) |
| In allowed set | Other path | Not blocked |

### Using a proxy (to test from a different IP)

```bash
# See which IP the target will see via the proxy
curl -s ifconfig.me -x http://PROXY_HOST:PORT

# Request through the proxy
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" -x http://PROXY_HOST:PORT "$TARGET/api/v1/protected/"
```

The WAF sees the **proxy's exit IP**, not yours. If the proxy IP is not in the allowed set → expect 403.

