## 15. Key Learnings & Gotchas

1. **NOT (Negate) is the #1 mistake.** If you want to block non-internal IPs, the IP set statement must be wrapped in `NotStatement`. Without it, you block your own internal users.

2. **Priority order matters.** First matching rule wins. An Allow at Priority 1 overrides a Block at Priority 5. Always check the full rule list and their priorities.

3. **"Exactly" match is strict.** The Host header `app.example.com` won't match `App.Example.Com` or `app.example.com:443`. Use text transformations (LOWERCASE) or CONTAINS for more tolerance.

4. **IP set updates replace the full list.** `update-ip-set` takes the complete list of addresses. If you only pass new IPs, old ones are removed. Always include existing + new.

5. **Lock tokens.** Every update to a Web ACL or IP set requires a lock token (from the latest get call). This prevents concurrent edits.

6. **WAF scope matters.** `REGIONAL` for ALB and API Gateway. `CLOUDFRONT` for CloudFront distributions (and must be in `us-east-1`).

7. **Sampled requests are your friend.** When debugging, check "Sampled requests" in the WAF console to see which rule matched and what action was taken. Much faster than guessing.

8. **DNS (Route 53) is separate from WAF.** DNS resolves the domain to the ALB. WAF runs on the ALB. If DNS points to the wrong ALB, WAF rules on the correct ALB won't apply.

9. **ACM certs must be in the same region as the ALB.** For CloudFront, certs must be in `us-east-1`.

10. **Test from multiple IPs.** Don't just test from your office (which is probably in the allowed set). Use a phone hotspot, home Wi-Fi, or a proxy to confirm blocking works for external IPs.

11. **Use `curl -s ifconfig.me`** to always know which IP the target sees. This is the IP the WAF checks, not your private/local IP.

12. **One Web ACL per ALB.** You can't attach multiple Web ACLs to one ALB. Put all rules in one Web ACL, organized by priority.

